Preamble
This Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement (the "Agreement"), dated as of November 1, 2020, and effective as of January 1, 2021 ("Effective Date"), subject to the conditions provided for in Section 3 of this Agreement, is between Vermont Electric Transmission Company, Inc. ("VETCO"), and the signatories listed as Phase I Participants listed in Attachment A to this Agreement (the signatories listed as Phase I Participants in Attachment A are hereinafter referred to as "Participants" or individually as a "Participant"; VETCO and the Participants are referred to herein as the "Parties" or "Party"). Recitals WHEREAS, the Parties were parties to the original Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, which was initially entered into on December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986 (the "Initial Agreement"); WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement provides for an initial term that expires as of November 1, 2020; WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement also provides an option to the Participants to extend the Initial Agreement for up to an additional twenty years under certain conditions specified therein; WHEREAS, those conditions being met, the Participants have exercised their right to extend the Initial Agreement for an additional twenty year term and wish to make revisions to the Initial Agreement appropriate for such extension; WHEREAS, this Agreement is an integral part of a set of interrelated agreements referred to herein as the Basic Agreements that set forth the rights and obligations regarding the Interconnection; WHEREAS, the fundamental purposes of the Basic Agreements including this Agreement, are to provide for: (a) secure financial support for the costs of the Interconnection, and appropriate investment return for the owners of the assets; and (b) certain benefits to the IRH in return for their financial support for the Interconnection, including but not limited to: (i) transmission rights to the transmission transfer capability on the Interconnection between New England and Quebec up to the maximum transfer capability of 2,000 megawatts ("MW"), as conditions permit; (ii) the ability to import and export energy, capacity and ancillary services between the ISO-NE and Hydro-Quebec transmission systems for commercial and reliability purposes, promoting economic and environmental benefits to customers in New England by facilitating the delivery of zero-carbon energy at a reasonable cost; and (iii) an operable Interconnection to allow for use of the Use Rights and to promote reliability and energy security related benefits to New England; WHEREAS, the other Basic Agreements are being renewed for twenty years until November 1, 2040, and WHEREAS, the Parties desire to amend and restate this Agreement, as amended and restated herein, effective as of January 1, 2021; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises, the concurrent execution of the other Basic Agreements hereinafter referred to, the mutual covenants hereinafter and therein set forth, and other good and valuable consideration, receipt whereof is hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: Section 1: Definitions Advisory Committee: shall mean the IRH Management Committee, as provided for under the Use Agreement. Basic Agreements: shall mean the following agreements: The Support Agreements, the Equity Funding Agreements and the Use Agreement. Combined Percentage Interest: shall be the combined percentage amount of Use Rights and financial obligations each of the IRH has under both the Phase I and II Support Agreements, as set forth in Attachment A to this Agreement. Entitlement Transaction: shall mean any transaction utilizing the Interconnection allowed under the Use Agreement other than an Emergency Energy transaction. Equity Funding Agreements: shall mean: (1) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Electric Company, Inc., dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended; and (2) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Corporation, dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended. Good Utility Practice: shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the New England region. Governmental Authority or Governmental Authorities: shall mean any executive, legislative, judicial, regulatory or administrative agency, body, commission, department, board, court, tribunal, arbitrating body or authority of the United States or any foreign country, or any state, local or other governmental subdivision thereof. Interconnection: shall mean the high-voltage, direct current ("HVDC") interconnection, transmission and converter terminal facilities on the United States side of the border interconnecting the Hydro-Quebec system and the ISO-NE system, provided for and described in the Basic Agreements, with a nominal transfer capability of 2,000 MW. Interconnection Rights Holders ("IRH"): shall mean the parties to the Support Agreements that have the financial obligation to pay for the costs of the United States portion of the Interconnection in exchange for the Use Rights granted under the Support Agreements. IRH Management Committee ("IMC"): shall mean the governance committee for the IRH, as provided for under the Use Agreement, and responsible for the collective management of the IRH's involvement in the Interconnection and the Basic Agreements. The IMC, and any successor to the IMC, is the Advisory Committee under this Agreement. ISO-NE: shall mean ISO New England Inc., the independent system operator and regional transmission organization for the New England control area, and any successor entity to ISO-NE. Participating Share: shall have the meaning provided in Section 5 of this Agreement. Phase I: shall mean the initial stage of the Interconnection in Vermont and New Hampshire, provided for and described in the Phase I Support Agreements. Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line: shall mean the transmission facilities described in the Amended and Restated Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement and constructed in New Hampshire as part of Phase I of the Interconnection. New England Electric Transmission Corporation (NEET) is the asset owner of the Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line. Phase I Support Agreements: shall mean: (i) this Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986, as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Terminal Facility Support Agreement originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986, as it may be subsequently amended. Phase I Vermont Transmission Line: shall mean the transmission facilities described in this Agreement and constructed in Vermont as part of Phase I of the Interconnection. VETCO is the asset owner of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. Phase II: shall mean the subsequent stage of construction of the Interconnection, provided for and described in the Phase II Support Agreements, that augmented the nominal transfer capability of the Interconnection to 2,000 MW through construction of an HVDC transmission line from the location of the Comerford Generating Station through New Hampshire to a new converter terminal facility adjacent to and interconnected with the Sandy Pond Substation in Ayer, Massachusetts. Phase II Support Agreements: shall mean: (i) the Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, and January 1, 1989, as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, amending and restating the Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, January 1, 1989, and January 1, 1990, as it may be subsequently amended. Support Agreements: shall mean the Phase I Support Agreements and the Phase II Support Agreements, collectively. Use Agreement: shall mean the Fourth Amended and Restated Use Agreement, which amends and restates the Agreement with Respect to Use of Quebec Interconnection, originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated September 1, 1985, November 19, 1997, April 8, 1998, June 29, 2001, and February 11, 2002, as it may be subsequently amended. Use Rights: shall mean the exclusive rights to use the transmission capacity of the Interconnection granted to the IRH under the Support Agreements in exchange for the financial commitment of the IRH to support the full costs of the interconnection in accordance with the Support Agreements. The Use Rights are further provided for and governed by the Use Agreement. Section 2: Basic Understandings Together with this Agreement for Phase I, some or all of the Participants are also participants in the Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement and the Phase II Support Agreements. The facilities covered under the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements are integrally related and interdependent facilities, and the Parties intend that they be treated accordingly under the Basic Agreements. The Basic Agreements are intended to work together as a set of interrelated agreements governing participation in the Interconnection and the rights and obligations that result from such participation. Phase I of the Interconnection consists of the United States portion a of a 450 kV HVDC transmission line from a terminal at the Des Cantons Substation on the Hydro-Quebec system near Sherbrooke, Quebec to the location of the former terminal having had a Nominal rating of 690 MW which was adjacent to a substation at the location of the Comerford Generating Station on the Connecticut River. (hereinafter referred to as Phase I). In 2012, the Phase I Terminal Facilities were retired and the substation interconnection was decommissioned, leaving the remaining Phase I HVDC facilities and equipment to be utilized solely with Phase II. The portion of Phase II in the United States consists of an extension of the Phase I HVDC transmission line from Phase I at the Comerford Generating Station location through New Hampshire to Sandy Pond in Massachusetts with additional Terminal Facilities installed at Sandy Pond that increased the prior transfer capacity from Hydro-Quebec to approximately 2,000 MW, where conditions permit in accordance with Good Utility Practice. The Parties have made commitments under the Basic Agreements to obtain the benefits of the Interconnection, as further described in the recitals above. In connection with the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, the parties also recognize certain other agreements and tariff provisions are important to the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. These other agreements include: (i) a certain Asset Owners Agreement between the asset owners of Interconnection facilities and the asset owners of the interconnected facilities in Quebec; (ii) the Interconnection Operators Agreement between the system operators in the United States and Quebec; (iii) the Phase II Maine Electric Power SVC Support Agreement between New England Hydro-Transmission Corp. and Maine Electric Power Company to provide for certain static var compensator facilities specified in that agreement important to the reliable operation of the Interconnection; (iv) the Transmission Service Administration Agreement among the IMC, ISO-NE and the Schedule 20A Service Providers; (v) the HVDC Transmission Operating Agreement among the Asset Owners and ISO-NE; (vi) certain agreements related to the improvements and reinforcements to AC transmission systems in Massachusetts necessitated by Phase II, and referred to as the "Phase II New England Power AC Facilities Support Agreement" and the "Phase II Boston Edison AC Facilities Support Agreement"; and (vii) the provisions of the ISO-NE tariff and any successor provisions that provide for HQ Interconnection Capability Credits (as defined in that tariff) or similar benefits to the IRH. The parties agree to act toward these other agreements and tariff provisions in such a way as to promote the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. Transmission services over the United States section of Phase I shall be on terms and conditions provided for in this Agreement and the other Support Agreements, agreed upon among the Participants in the Use Agreement, and as otherwise provided for under the requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable transmission tariffs. The provisions of this Agreement cover the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. Attachment B to this Agreement provides a more detailed description of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. In accordance with the provisions of this Agreement and for the duration of its term, VETCO agrees to build any necessary and otherwise agreed upon upgrades to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, and to own, operate, and maintain the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, and each Participant hereby agrees to support the costs of capital investments in, operation, maintenance, and administration of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line in accordance with and subject to the provisions of this Agreement. Each Participant represents that it made its own independent investigations and inquiries into the projected costs and benefits of this Agreement as it deemed appropriate and did not rely upon representations (other than those contained in this Agreement) of VETCO or its affiliates in deciding to enter into this Agreement. The sharing of benefits and the coordination of rights among the Participants associated with the Interconnection is set forth in the Use Agreement. The Use Agreement also permits each Participant to engage in Entitlement Transactions. Each Participant acknowledges that the benefits of participating in this Agreement and in the Use Agreement are the fundamental considerations for its signing of this Agreement and making the significant commitments to each other Participant specified herein and to the participants in the other Support Agreements. VETCO is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Vermont Electric Power Company, Inc. (VELCO). During the term of this Agreement, VETCO will limit its activities to those necessary or desirable consistent with Good Utility Practice in connection with the Phase I Transmission Line. In order to minimize financing costs, VETCO will use its best efforts to obtain the maximum prudent amount of permanent debt financing at reasonable rates with maturities approximating, to the extent practicable, the then remaining useful life of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line or to secure other advantageous financial arrangements, such as leasing. VELCO and VETCO will enter into a capital funds arrangement under which VELCO will provide VETCO with equity funds. Such arrangement will provide for VELCO to supply equity funds for VETCO's capital requirements but not to exceed $12,500,000. However, if VETCO determines that, despite its intent to limit the use of equity funds to the amounts referred to above, it is unable to reasonably finance capital costs of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line using such limited amounts of common equity, it shall bring such matter before the Advisory Committee. After meeting with the Advisory Committee, VETCO may, at its option, request that VELCO provide the additional equity funds necessary to finance the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and VELCO may provide such funds. Subject to the limitations set forth above, during the term of this Agreement, VETCO shall use its best efforts to maintain the ratio of equity investment to total capital that would be most cost-effective for the Participants. Section 3: Conditions Precedent to Obligations A. General: The effectiveness of this Agreement, and all rights, obligations, and performance of the Parties, are subject to (a) the Parties obtaining all necessary regulatory approvals, consents, or other actions of Governmental Authorities having jurisdiction, (b) the execution of all of the Support Agreements and the Use Agreement by the parties thereto; and (c) the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission accepting the offer of settlement pertaining to this Agreement, including all FERC-jurisdictional contracts appended thereto, without condition or modification or with only those conditions or modifications subsequently agreed to by all the parties to that settlement. The Effective Date of this Agreement shall be on January 1, 2021, or on the date the conditions precedent specified above have been met, if later. Notwithstanding anything else in this Section 3, in the event all other conditions precedent are met, the effectiveness of this Agreement shall not be delayed if one or more Participants in the States of Maine and Vermont are in the process of obtaining necessary regulatory approvals, consents, or other actions of Governmental Authorities in Maine and Vermont having jurisdiction ("Maine and Vermont Governmental Approvals"), provided that: (1) the Participants in the States of Maine and Vermont will remain subject to all terms of conditions of this Agreement while such Maine and Vermont Governmental Approvals are pending, including but not limited to the absolute and unconditional obligations of each Participant in accordance with Section 14 to make payments hereunder, and to perform and observe all other agreements on its part contained herein; and (2) in the event a Participant in the States of Maine and Vermont provides written notice to New England Hydro that it has not obtained a necessary Maine and Vermont Governmental Approval, all rights of such Participant under this Agreement shall be terminated as of the date of such notice and the provisions of Section 15 governing the treatment of a terminated Participant shall apply. Without limiting the foregoing, all obligations of VETCO hereunder are subject to obtaining all necessary regulatory approvals authorizing VETCO to charge the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge described in Section 12 hereof. Since VELCO and Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Company (MMWEC), and any successor in interest thereto, represent a number of member systems, VELCO is deemed to have signed on behalf of all its respective systems listed in Schedule I hereto, and MMWEC is deemed to have signed as representative for all its respective systems listed in Schedule II hereto. The liability of MMWEC hereunder is a special obligation payable solely from revenues derived by MMWEC under contracts to be entered into with its members for payment of their proportionate shares of costs incurred under the Support. MMWEC may enter into such a contract with Pascoag Utility District as if it were a member. B. Representations and Warranties of the Parties: Each Party hereby represents and warrants that the following statements are true and correct as of the Effective Date: 1. General Representations and Warranties of the Parties (i) Organization; and Qualification. The Party is duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the jurisdiction of its organization and has full power and authority to own, lease and operate its assets and properties to the extent owned, leased and operated and to transact the business in which it is engaged. The Party is duly qualified or licensed to do business and is in good standing in each jurisdiction in which the property owned, leased or operated by it or the nature of the business transacted by it makes such qualification or licensure necessary, except where the failure to be so qualified or licensed or in good standing would not, individually or in the aggregate, have a material adverse effect on its assets and properties.. (ii) Authority Relative to this Agreement. The Party has full power and authority to execute, deliver and perform this Agreement and to carry out its obligations contemplated by this Agreement. The execution and delivery of this Agreement and the performance of the obligations of the Party contemplated hereby have been duly and validly authorized by all requisite corporate action, and this Agreement has been duly executed and delivered by such Party and constitutes the legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party, enforceable against the Party in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent conveyance, reorganization, moratorium, and other similar laws now or hereafter in effect affecting creditors' rights and remedies generally and subject, as to enforceability, to general principles of equity, including principles of commercial reasonableness, good faith and fair dealing (regardless of whether enforcement is sought in a proceeding at law or in equity). (iii) Consents and Approvals, No Violations. Other than as set forth in Attachment C, no declaration, authorization, consent or approval, notice to or registration or filing with any Governmental Authority is required for the execution, delivery and performance by such Party of its obligations contemplated by this Agreement. None of the execution, delivery and performance by such Party of its obligations contemplated by this Agreement conflicts with or will result in a breach or violation of such entity's organizational documents or any applicable law, rule, regulation, order or judgment, or contract, agreement or instrument by which such Party is bound or its assets affected. (iv) The execution, delivery, and performance by the Party of the Agreement do not (a) contravene the Party's charter documents, by-laws, or legislative act creating the Party, (b) to the Party's knowledge, violate any applicable law, rule, regulation, order, writ, judgment, injunction, decree, or award by which the Party is bound, (c) to the Party's knowledge, violate any indenture, instrument, agreement, or bond resolution by which the Party is bound, or (d) to the Party's knowledge, result in or require the creation or the imposition of any lien pursuant to the provisions of any indenture, instrument, agreement, or bond resolution by which the Party is bound (v) Legal Proceedings. To the Party's knowledge there are no legal or arbitral proceedings by or before any Governmental Authority, now pending or (to the actual knowledge of such Party) threatened, that if adversely determined would reasonably be expected to materially impair such Party's ability to perform its obligations contemplated by this Agreement. 2. MMWEC Representations Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Company ("MMWEC") is a Participant under this Agreement. MMWEC is a party to certain contracts, undertakings, or agreements with electric systems listed in Schedule II hereto (for these purposes including Pascoag, Rhode Island) and referred to in this Agreement as "Massachusetts Systems", and which electric systems have entered into the MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project dated as of July 15, 1982 (the "MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement"). In pertinent part, the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement imposes absolute and unconditional obligations on each Massachusetts System to: (1) pay its proportionate shares of all costs incurred by MMWEC under this Agreement; and (2) fix, revise and collect fees or charges for electric power and energy and other services sold at least sufficient to provide revenues adequate to meet its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement. MMWEC makes certain representations as set forth in this Section 3 representing unconditionally that all consents, approvals, and authorizations have been obtained by the Massachusetts Systems in connection with each such system's performance of its obligations under its MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement with MMWEC and that each such MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement imposes absolute and unconditional obligations on such systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred under this Agreement by MMWEC and has been duly authorized, executed, and delivered and is a binding commitment of such electric systems enforceable in accordance with its terms. In order that percentages of participation be consistent among the Basic Agreements, both the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and the Second MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project Phase II (dated as of June 15, 1988, as amended, which agreement covers MMWEC's commitments for Phase II) cover the necessary commitments for each Basic Agreement. MMWEC represents and warrants to VETCO and each other Party that the following statements are true and correct as of the Effective Date: (i) MMWEC has executed thirty (30) separate, but identical, MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements with each of the Massachusetts Systems dated as of July 15, 1982, as amended. (ii) The Massachusetts Systems have full power and authority to execute, deliver and perform their MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and to carry out the obligations contemplated by such MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement. The execution and delivery of the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements and the performance of the obligations of the Massachusetts Systems contemplated thereby have been duly and validly authorized by all requisite corporate action, and each of the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements has been duly executed and delivered by such Massachusetts System and constitutes the legal, valid and binding obligation of such Massachusetts System, enforceable against the Massachusetts System in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent conveyance, reorganization, moratorium, and other similar laws now or hereafter in effect affecting creditors' rights and remedies generally and subject, as to enforceability, to general principles of equity, including principles of commercial reasonableness, good faith and fair dealing (regardless of whether enforcement is sought in a proceeding at law or in equity). (iii) The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements impose absolute and unconditional obligations on each of the Massachusetts Systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred by MMWEC under this Agreement and to fix, revise and collect fees or charges for electric power and energy and other services, facilities and commodities sold, furnished or supplied through its electric department or system a least sufficient to provide revenues adequate to meet its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and to pay any and all other amounts payable from or constituting a charge and lien upon such revenues, including amounts sufficient to pay the principal of and interest on all bonds issued by the Massachusetts System for electric purposes. (iv) Pursuant to a Waiver and Certification executed in December 2018 ("MMWEC Participant Waiver and Certification"), each Massachusetts System has certified to MMWEC, among other things, that: a. It is a participant under a MMWEC Participation Agreement; b. It is in compliance with all of its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; c. Its obligations to make payments to MMWEC and perform its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement are absolute and unconditional; d. No assignment, transfer or sale of any interest by the Massachusetts System relieves it of any of its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; e. As necessary or advisable, MMWEC may execute and/or approve additional contracts and amendments associated with the Transmission Facilities and the Massachusetts System agrees to accept its pro rata share of the obligations and benefits of such contracts as if such contracts were originally referenced in the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; f. All other rights and obligations of MMWEC and the Massachusetts System under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement are confirmed and acknowledged; g. The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements, and all rights and obligations thereunder, remain in full force and effect during the term of this Agreement, as may be amended and extended; and h. The Massachusetts System will provide to MMWEC any additional documents which are reasonably necessary for MMWEC's execution of additional agreements or amendments associated with this Agreement. (v) All consents, declarations, registrations, authorizations, and regulatory approvals required for MMWEC to enter into the Agreement and for MMWEC and the Massachusetts Systems to enter into the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements have been obtained and/or fulfilled. (vi) The liability of MMWEC under this Agreement is a special obligation payable solely from revenues derived by MMWEC pursuant to the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements. By a board resolution MMWEC has agreed not to grant to any other party any lien upon, pledge or assignment of revenues derived from the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements except in the case of the issuance by MMWEC of bonds, notes or other evidences of indebtedness under the terms of which proceeds of any such borrowings shall be applied to payments due to NEET and VETCO, as their interests may appear under the Support Agreements, and interest and related fees and expenses in connection with such borrowing arrangements ("MMWEC Borrowing"). The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements provide that the monies received as payments by MMWEC under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements for support charges (as such term is defined in this Agreement) will be applied first to the payments due NEET and VETCO, as their interests may appear under the Support Agreements, and then to others; except in the event of an MMWEC Borrowing, the MMWEC Borrowing shall have the first priority for payments from revenues received by MMWEC under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements. Section 4: Effective Date and Term This Agreement shall become effective upon the Effective Date, as provided for in Section 3 of this Agreement. This Agreement shall expire on October 31, 2040; provided, however, that if the Phase I Transmission Line is operational and there are commitments to support the full costs of the Phase I Transmission Line, a Participant shall be entitled, to elect to continue participation for an additional period not to exceed of 20 years upon the terms and conditions of this Agreement (with any amendments mutually agreed to by the Parties). Each Participant must provide notice in writing of its election to continue participation no later than by July 1, 2035 to the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall determine the length of any such extended term by August 1, 2035. The Advisory Committee must provide notice in writing no later than by November 1, 2035, to VETCO of the Participant elections to continue participation and the length of such extended term. Notification will be given to each Participant by VETCO of such option to continue participation by no later than May 1, 2035. VETCO shall determine, in its sole discretion, whether the Participants electing to continue participation reasonably can be anticipated to support the full cost of the Transmission Facilities during the proposed extended term and shall inform each electing Participant of that determination no later than November 1, 2038. In order to inform such determination, the Participants seeking to renew shall, upon request, provide documentation that VETCO may require in its discretion addressing the ability of those Participants to support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities over the proposed additional term, including but not limited to representations from all Participants and credit support from any Participants seeking to renew that are not "investment grade" Participants. It is anticipated by the Participants VETCO that during the period November 1, 2035 through November 1, 2038, VETCO and the Participants electing to continue participation shall work collectively and in good faith to assist VETCO in its determination. As of November 1, 2038, if the determination of VETCO, in its sole discretion, is that the Participants electing to continue participation cannot support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities, VETCO shall so notify all Participants stating the reasons for such determination. As a result of such determination, VETCO shall be free to take any action it deems appropriate including, but not limited to termination of the Agreement as of November 1, 2040, in accordance with Section 16, restructuring of the Agreement, continuing operation of the Transmission Facilities under alternative cost recovery provisions to be approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, sale of the Transmission Facilities or any other action it deems appropriate in light of the circumstances and facts known at the time of such determination and shall notify all Participants of such proposed action on November 1, 2038. Each Participant which is also a participant under the Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement or the Phase II Support Agreements shall exercise its rights and take all actions under those agreements to allow for the continued operation of the Interconnection for the full term of this Agreement; provided that the foregoing provision shall in no way limit the Advisory Committee's rights to act under this Agreement. Section 5: Participating Shares Each Participant shall have and be charged in accordance with a percentage interest in all of the rights and obligations hereunder (which percentage interest, as from time to time adjusted hereunder in accordance with the computation provided for in this Section 5, being hereinafter referred to as its "Participating Share"). The Participating Share of each Participant under this Agreement initially shall be in the amount set forth in Attachment A to this Agreement. After the Effective Date, each Participant shall be entitled to transfer any or all of its Participating Share to one or more other Participants, provided such Participant gives at least six months advance written notice to VETCO, the other Participants and the Advisory Committee. After the Effective Date of this Agreement, VETCO, after consulting with the Advisory Committee, shall adjust such Participating Share amounts as of the last day of any month in which there is a change in the number of Participants or any change in the interest of any Participant as herein provided, including the termination of any Participant's participation in this Agreement. VETCO shall provide notice to the Advisory Committee within 30 calendar days of any such change in percentage interest. Any reallocation of Participating Shares for termination of a Participant shall be made pro rata among all remaining Participants, so as to maintain the relative proportion of Participating Shares among the remaining Participants. Section 6: Relationship among Participants The rights and obligations of the Participants hereunder are several and not joint. The rights and obligations of VETCO hereunder are also several and not joint with those of the Participants, or any one thereof. There is no intention to create by this Agreement, or by any grant, lease, license, or activity related to this Agreement, an association, joint venture, trust, or partnership or to impose on any Participant trust or partnership rights or obligations and any such implied intention is expressly negated. Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, no Participant shall have by virtue of this Agreement or of any such grant, lease, license, or activity, the right or power to bind any other Participant without its express written consent. Section 7: Advisory Committee The IMC, as provided for under the Use Agreement and acting in accordance with the governance provisions of the Use Agreement, shall be the Advisory Committee and shall approve the by-laws of the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall advise VETCO on all major matters of concern to the Participants regarding the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and the Interconnection. VETCO shall make prompt proposals for decisions on any such matters, and shall not act without approval from the Advisory Committee unless it reasonably believes that failure to act would be inconsistent with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement and provides such opinion to the Advisory Committee in writing. The Advisory Committee shall have the power and responsibilities set forth in this Agreement and the Use Agreement and shall adopt its own by-laws, provided that (i) voting shall be by Combined Percentage Interest at the time of the vote, (ii) a vote of two-thirds or more of Participating Shares is required to approve a VETCO proposal or to take other affirmative action, and absent such a vote the proposal shall be deemed to be rejected by the Advisory Committee, and (iii) one or more Participants having Participating Shares of at least 10% in the aggregate may by reasonable written notice to all Participants call a meeting of the Advisory Committee. In addition, the Advisory Committee has authority in connection with increasing the rating of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line beyond 690 MW, determination of fair market value of property or property rights rented by (but not to) VETCO from other utilities, and termination or cancellation of construction or operation of the Transmission Line as specified in Sections 9, 12, and 16, respectively, of this Agreement. Each Participant shall be responsible for all of its expenses related to membership on the Advisory Committee. The costs of the Advisory Committee shall be treated as a Support Charge and paid for by the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge and payment provisions of this Agreement and the other Support Agreements. Section 8: Design and Construction of Upgrades to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line
VETCO shall have sole responsibility for the design, engineering, procurement, installation, and all other aspects of the construction of any upgrades to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, and any modifications or additions made to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, all in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objective being to achieve an appropriate balance among minimization of construction cost, minimization of operation and maintenance cost, licensing and environmental considerations, and safety and reliability of service. In carrying out these activities, VETCO shall consult with the Advisory Committee in accordance with this Agreement and consistent with Good Utility Practice, and may utilize the services of its affiliates and may also select and employ a design engineering firm, a construction engineering firm, and such other engineering, consulting, and construction firms as it considers desirable. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of VETCO, such affiliate will charge no more than it charges to its other affiliates in accordance with applicable laws and regulations. In its design and construction of any upgrades to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, VETCO shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of the transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. VETCO shall consult with the Advisory Committee concerning any major changes to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line that VETCO believes will have a significant effect on the Support Charges, or upon the reliability or availability of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, and shall follow the recommendations of the Advisory Committee to the extent reasonably practicable, unless VETCO reasonably believes that such recommendations are not in accordance with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement; provided, however, that a failure of the Advisory Committee to provide a recommendation shall not be allowed to delay work on the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line to such an extent that it would have a material adverse effect on the cost of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line or the time schedule for the work's completion. During the course of any such work, VETCO shall also furnish quarterly reports to the Advisory Committee with respect to the progress of the work and an annual report to the Advisory Committee of actual and estimated expenditures. In addition to the responsibilities set forth in this Section 8, VETCO is the holder of the Presidential Permit for the Interconnection, and shall ensure that it maintains the Presidential Permit and meets its conditions. Section 9: Operation and Maintenance of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line VETCO shall have sole responsibility for the operation and maintenance of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objectives being to operate the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line as efficiently, economically, safely, and reliably as feasible. VETCO shall also use its best efforts to coordinate the operation and maintenance of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line with the operation and maintenance of the other Interconnection facilities, with Hydro-Quebec's transmission system, and with ISO-NE. VETCO shall operate and maintain the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line in accordance with all applicable reliability standards. In furtherance of its responsibility, VETCO may, from time to time and subject to approval by the Advisory Committee, designate a company, which need not be a Participant, to operate and maintain the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of VETCO, such affiliate shall charge not more than it charges its other affiliates. In its operation and maintenance of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, VETCO shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of the transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. VETCO shall consult with the Advisory Committee concerning any major changes in operation and maintenance that VETCO believes will have a significant effect on the cost of operating the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and the Interconnection, or upon its reliability or availability, and shall follow the recommendations of the Advisory Committee to the extent reasonably practicable, unless VETCO reasonably believes that such recommendations are not in accordance with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement, and states its reasons in writing to the Advisory Committee; provided, however, that a failure of the Advisory Committee to provide a recommendation shall not be allowed to delay any repair or replacement on the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. VETCO shall furnish quarterly reports to the Advisory Committee with respect to the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Line and an annual report to the Advisory Committee, of estimated operation and maintenance expenses. Section 10: VETCO Relationship to Participants In carrying out its responsibilities under Sections 8 and 9, VETCO agrees that it shall use its best efforts to act for the collective benefit of the Participants and VETCO, to include in its contracts with independent contractors the customary provisions for assuring professional and workmanlike performance, including warranties, insurance coverage and other protections consistent with Good Utility Practice, and to enforce its rights under such contracts against the other contracting parties to the maximum extent reasonable, reserving the discretion to settle claims on whatever basis it deems prudent. As provided in Section 12 below, all costs of construction, including damages caused by the risks of negligence and other risks of construction in excess of the recoveries obtained from offending parties, shall be included as part of the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and all costs of operating the Transmission Line, including damages caused by risks of negligence or other risks of operation in excess of any recoveries obtained from offending parties, shall be included in VETCO's operating costs. Section 11: Transmission Services Within its ability to do so, consistent with Good Utility Practice, VETCO shall perform its obligations under this Agreement so as to enable Participants to obtain the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, as further described in the recitals to this Agreement. Each Participant is hereby granted an exclusive right to use its Participating Share of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line in accordance with the Use Agreement and applicable requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable rate schedules and transmission tariffs. Section 12: Support Charge Commencing in the month following the Effective Date, and in each month thereafter, a Support Charge shall be determined. The Support Charge for each month shall be equal to VETCO's Total Cost of Service Related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line for such month. The "Total Cost of Service Related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line" for any month shall be the sum of (a) VETCO's Operating Expenses for such month with respect to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, plus (b) an amount equal to one-twelfth of the Composite Percentage for such month times the Net Rate Base attributable to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, less (c) 50% of any other income received by VETCO resulting from the use of facilities supported by the Participants under this Agreement. If the Effective Date is not on the first day of the month, an appropriate proration of the amount determined in (b) above shall be made for such first payment only. "Uniform System" shall mean the Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) for Class A and Class B Public Utilities and Licensees, as from time to time in effect. VETCO's "Operating Expenses" shall include all amounts related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and properly chargeable to operating expense accounts less any applicable credits thereto in accordance with the Uniform System including, but not limited to, operation and maintenance expense such as rent on leased property and administrative and general expenses, state and federal income and franchise taxes, property taxes, payroll taxes, any other taxes not based on income, and depreciation and/or amortization expense; it being understood that for purposes of this Agreement, depreciation and/or amortization shall be at a rate sufficient to recover the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line (including estimated cost of removal, less any salvage value, which salvage value, for the purposes of calculating such depreciation, will not exceed the amount of cost of removal) over the shorter of (i) the estimated remaining useful life of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line as determined by VETCO or (ii) the remaining term of VETCO's permanent debt financings or other financing arrangements related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, adjusted for multiple maturities and repayment schedules. The allowance for state and federal income taxes included in Operating Expenses shall reflect the normalization of timing differences, the flow-through of permanent differences between book income and tax income, and amortization of excess or deficient accumulated deferred income taxes resulting from the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act ("TCJA") and any future changes in federal or state tax laws. VETCO, as the tax owner of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, is entitled to the benefits and burdens of such ownership for tax purposes. VETCO shall normalize investment tax credits over the depreciation or amortization period referred to above in accordance with the requirements of the then applicable Internal Revenue Code. To the extent that VETCO has tax losses or investment tax credits which are utilized in a consolidated return with VELCO, VETCO will receive a timely cash payment from VELCO equal to the actual reduction in current tax liability, if any, resulting from the inclusion of VETCO in such consolidated return, provided, however, that VETCO will receive such cash payment only to the extent it creates savings in the consolidated return over the amount the taxes would have been without the inclusion of VETCO. This provision is included so that VETCO can and will comply with applicable tax rules and retain the rights to use accelerated cost recovery systems and investment tax credits on the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. The "Investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line" shall be the aggregate amount incurred at any time either before or after commercial operation of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, which relates to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and is properly chargeable to VETCO's utility plant accounts (including construction work in progress) in accordance with the Uniform System. "Composite Percentage" shall be computed as of the last day of each month (the "computation date"), and for calculations performed during any month the composite percentage shall be that computed as of the most recent computation date. Composite Percentage as of a computation date shall be the sum of (i) Return on Equity then in effect multiplied by the percentage which equity investment as of such date is of the total capital as of such date; plus (ii) the effective interest rate per annum of each principal amount of indebtedness outstanding on such date for money borrowed, whether long term or short term, multiplied by the percentage which each such principal amount is of total capital as of such date. "Return on Equity" shall be 11.07%. This provision establishing an 11.07% Return on Equity shall be subject to a moratorium on any changes made or proposed by any Party under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act. The moratorium period shall commence on the filing date of Agreement with the Commission and shall end five years from the Commission-approved Effective Date. During this moratorium, no Party may propose any increase or decrease to the 11.07% Return on Equity under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act including through any Return on Equity incentive adder or through any adjustment to the Return on Equity as a result of a change in the Commission's Return on Equity policies. "Equity Investment" as of any date shall consist of the sum of (i) all amounts theretofore paid to VETCO for all capital stock theretofore issued, plus all capital contributions, less the sum of any amounts paid by VETCO in the form of stock retirements, repurchases or redemptions or return of capital; plus (ii) any credit balance in the capital surplus account not included under (iii), and any credit balance in the earned surplus (retained earnings) account on the books of VETCO as of such date. "Total Capital" as of any date shall be the Equity Investment plus the total of all indebtedness then outstanding for money borrowed. The "Net Rate Base" for the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line shall be determined as of the Effective Date and semiannually as of June 30 and December 31 thereafter and shall consist of (i) the Investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, less (ii) the amount of any accumulated provision for depreciation and amortization related to Investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission line, less (iii) the amount of any reserve for deferred income taxes received by VETCO, such deferred income taxes to include deferred income taxes due to accelerated depreciation and construction tax benefits related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line, plus (iv) the amount of any regulatory asset for deficient accumulated deferred income taxes resulting from the TCJA and any future changes in federal or state tax laws, less (v) the amount of any regulatory liability for excess accumulated deferred income taxes resulting from the TCJA and any future changes in federal or state tax laws, less (vi) the amount of any unamortized investment tax credits received by VETCO, plus (vii) such allowances related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line for materials and supplies, prepaid items, and cash working capital as may from time to time be determined by VETCO as reasonably necessary and in accordance with accepted utility accounting practice. Any allowance for cash working capital shall be limited to that not sufficiently recovered through the use of estimated billing for the current month. The Support Charge shall also include the costs of the Advisory Committee provided for under this Agreement and the Use Agreement, which shall be allocated to the IRH on the basis of Combined Percentage Interest. VETCO will provide a fully populated "ADIT worksheet" in the form attached hereto and incorporated herein to track excess or deficient ADIT as a result of the TCJA and any future changes in federal or state tax laws. The monthly statements issued to the Participants in accordance with Section 13 will include a fully populated ADIT worksheet whenever there is a change to VETCO's excess or deficient ADIT. Section 13: Payments Commencing on or about the tenth day of each month after the Effective Date, VETCO shall render to each Participant a statement for its Participating Share of all amounts due hereunder for such month, calculated on a one-month lag using actual results for such month. Each Participant shall promptly pay to VETCO the entire amount shown thereon. Any statement which is not paid within 25 days after its date shall bear interest compounded monthly from the date of the bill to the date when payment is made at an annual rate equal to 120% of the current interest rate on prime commercial loans from time to time in effect at VETCO's lender at that time. Section 15: Default A. In the event of default by any Party in any obligation pursuant to this Agreement, any other Party is free to invoke such remedies at law or in equity as may be deemed appropriate. B. No delay or failure in the performance of any obligation by VETCO shall be deemed to exist if it is the result of an "uncontrollable force." The term "uncontrollable force" shall be deemed to mean any cause beyond the reasonable control of VETCO, which VETCO could not reasonably have been expected to avoid by exercise of due diligence and foresight, including, without limiting the generality of the foregoing, storm, flood, lightning, earthquake, fire, explosion, failure of facilities not due to lack of proper care or maintenance, civil disturbance, labor disturbance, sabotage, war, national emergency, or restraint by court or public authority. In such event, VETCO shall use reasonable diligence to notify the Participants of such event, to place itself in a position to fulfill its obligations hereunder, and if unable to fulfill any obligation by reason of an uncontrollable force, VETCO shall exercise reasonable diligence to remove such disability with reasonable dispatch. C. In the event of (i) a Participant's failure to perform any obligation under this Agreement (other than a payment obligation under Section 16 or 17), including a failure to make any payment to VETCO within 15 days after the date of any statement rendered by VETCO, which failure continues for more than thirty days after written notice of such failure has been given to such Participant by VETCO, or (ii) initiation of any proceeding with respect to any insolvency, bankruptcy, reorganization, or liquidation of a Participant, VETCO may, in addition to any other rights or remedies that it may have against such Participant, by reason thereof, terminate as of the date of such written notice or the initiation of such proceedings all rights of such Participant under this Agreement; provided, however, that no such termination may be made by VETCO in the event of initiation of any proceeding with respect to any insolvency, bankruptcy, reorganization or liquidation of a Participant occurring after any cancellation, termination, or permanent shutdown of the construction or operation of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. Such Participant shall be given written notice that VETCO has terminated such defaulting Participant's participation hereunder and thereafter VETCO shall reallocate the Participating Shares of the other Participants hereunder pursuant to Section 5 of this Agreement. Thereupon VETCO shall be entitled to receive all amounts retained or retainable by the payment agent under the Use Agreement on account of such defaulting Participant's share of any benefits payable thereunder with respect to the month to which the default relates or any month prior thereto such amount to be applied first toward the payment of the defaulted obligation hereunder with interest and the balance, if any, to be retained by VETCO as liquidated damages. Upon such termination, the defaulting Participant, in addition to any other amounts owed to VETCO, shall pay to VETCO an amount equal to its Participating Share of the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line (including any costs of removal and disposal) less any depreciation and amortization related to the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line to such time. VETCO shall first credit any such amounts received from the defaulting Participant against any payment obligations owed to VETCO by the defaulting Participant and then to future payment obligations of the remaining Participants. Section 16: Termination, Suspension, Delay or Shutdown of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line
If, at any time, VETCO determines that continued investment in upgrades in, construction or operation and maintenance of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line is not advisable, VETCO shall consult with the Advisory Committee and, if the Advisory Committee approves, or if VETCO reasonably believes and explains in writing to the Advisory Committee that Good Utility Practice so requires, VETCO may delay, restrict or suspend investment in upgrades in, construction or operation and maintenance of the Phase I Transmission Line or may shut down the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line for a brief or extended period or permanently. In any case in which VETCO determines that safety considerations require an immediate shutdown, it shall proceed without affording to the Advisory Committee an opportunity to comment, but shall provide a report to the Advisory Committee promptly thereafter. Subject to the provisions of Section 17, if operation of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line is terminated, or if the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line is permanently shut down, then one of the following shall occur: (a) If such event or decision is approved by the Advisory Committee, each Participant shall pay to VETCO within ninety days of VETCO's notice of the occurrence of such event or decision its Participating Share of the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line less any depreciation and amortization to such time and all costs resulting from the cancellation. Such costs shall also include the costs of the total or partial demolition and disposal of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. The Participants shall be credited with any actual salvage value received by VETCO including the proceeds from any sale to an affiliate of VETCO. Upon termination of this Agreement, VETCO retains the right to sell the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line at fair value to any affiliate of VETCO. (b) If such event or decision is not approved by the Advisory Committee, each Participant shall pay to VETCO its Participating Share of the total costs described in subparagraph (a) above within the time period specified therein. Thereupon, VETCO will transfer its rights, assets, and obligations related to the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line to the Participants or any group thereof which they may designate. Section 17: Cancellation by Participants In the event that (i) the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line is damaged to the extent of being completely or substantially completely destroyed, or (ii) the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line is taken by exercise of the right of eminent domain or a similar right or power, then, and in each such case, any Participant may cancel its participation in this Agreement. Such cancellation shall be effected by written notice given by the Participant to VETCO. In the event of such cancellation, all continuing obligations of the Participant hereunder, other than payment obligations with respect to periods up to the date of cancellation for which the Participant shall remain fully liable hereunder, shall cease forthwith. If at any time VETCO determines that the next computation of the Participating Share allocations to be made pursuant to Section 5 could result in the Participating Share of any Participant having increased by more than 50% over the amount of its Participating Share at the commencement of this Agreement, then prior to the date as of which such next computation would be made VETCO shall give written notice of such fact to such Participant. Each such Participant shall then have the option, exercisable by written notice to VETCO and all other Participants within 30 days of VETCO's written notice, to elect to terminate its participation hereunder as of the date of VETCO's written notice (the "effective date of termination"), provided, that such Participant within 90 days of its election pays to VETCO (i) its Participating Share (as in effect on the effective date of termination) of the investment in the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line (including any costs of removal and disposal) less any depreciation and amortization to the effective date of termination and (ii) all its other obligations to VETCO hereunder. No termination of this Agreement shall relieve any party of any obligation arising prior to the effective date of such termination. In addition, notwithstanding the termination of this Agreement for other Purposes, this Agreement shall continue in effect to the extent necessary to provide for final billings, billing adjustments and payments. Section 18 [This section was intentionally left blank.] Section 19: Miscellaneous A. Insurance. VETCO shall, at all times during the term of this Agreement, keep the Phase I Transmission Line insured against such risks as electric utility companies, similarly situated, constructing and operating like properties, usually insure against. *** Indirect IRH and "Others" identified in italics. "Others", listed separately, are: (i) MMWEC Participants under the MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project dated July 15, 1982 ("MMWEC Phase I PA") and under the Second MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project Phase II dated June 15, 1988 ("MMWEC Phase II PA"); and (ii) NSTAR East and West. The MMWEC Participants identified as "Others" are not IRHs or Indirect IRHs as defined in the Use Agreement (see footnote 3). The Percentage Interests of MMWEC, an IRH, under the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements and the Use Agreement, are listed in this Attachment A in column entries associated with these MMWEC Participants in order to (a) clarify the Participant's Share of MMWEC Project Capability of these MMWEC Participants under and as defined in the MMWEC Phase I PA and the MMWEC Phase II PA and (b) enable recognition of these MMWEC Participant Shares of Project Capability under the MMWEC Phase I PA and MMWEC Phase II PA for purposes of updating Schedule 3.13(a) of the Phase I/II HVDC-TF Transmission Service Administration Agreement dated November 29, 2011.
1 MMWEC Phase I Participant and Phase II IRH -- This system is both an MMWEC Participant under the MMWEC Phase I PA and an IRH on its own under the Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement and the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement. This system purchases, through the MMWEC Phase I PA, a Participant's Share of Project Capability.
2 Phase I Percentage Interest for MMWEC Phase I Participant and Phase II IRH. This system is a MMWEC Participant under the MMWEC Phase I PA and an IRH with respect to Phase II. The Phase I percentage interest represents this system's Participant's Share of MMWEC Project Capability under and defined in the MMWEC Phase I PA and is provided here rather than in MMWEC's row solely to enable the calculation of the Combined Percentage Interests of the system as a Phase II IRH and as a MMWEC Phase I Participant under the MMWEC Phase I PA. This percentage and the percentage in the Column "Combined Percentage Interest" do not: (i) render the system an IRH or Indirect IRH for purposes of Phase I; (ii) change the status of this system as a MMWEC Participant under the MMWEC Phase I PA; or (iii) impede the right of this system under the MMWEC Phase I PA to effect through MMWEC a transfer of all or a portion of its MMWEC Phase I PA Participant's Share of Project Capability, consistent with MMWEC's rights under the MMWEC Phase I PA and as an IRH under the Use Agreement and the Phase I/II Transmission Service Administration Agreement. This system's Phase II Percentage Interest is its percentage interest as an IRH, independent of its MMWEC Project Capability purchased through the MMWEC Phase I PA.
3 MMWEC Phase I and II Participant - This system is an MMWEC Participant under both the MMWEC Phase I PA and the MMWEC Phase II PA. The system is not an IRH or an Indirect IRH as defined in the Use Agreement. Further clarification of the interests of the MMWEC Participants and why they are included as "Others" in this Attachment A is provided in note ***.
3a MMWEC Phase I Participant Only- Sterling Municipal Light Department is a MMWEC Participant under the MMWEC Phase I PA. It originally was a Phase II IRH, but is no longer a Phase II IRH. It is not a MMWEC Participant under the MMWEC Phase II PA.
4 Phase I and Phase II Percentage Interest for MMWEC Phase I and II Participant. Percentage represents a portion of MMWEC's Percentage interests as an IRH which is allocated to the system based on its Participant's Share of Project Capability under, and as defined in, the MMWEC Phase I PA and MMWEC Phase II PA, respectively. The percentages reflect MMWEC Phase I and II Participants' Shares of Project Capability for purposes of amending Schedule 3.13(a) of the Phase I/II HVDC-TF Transmission Service Administration Agreement dated November 29, 2011.
